http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/title.value: Rhode Island K-12 Grade Span Expectations in the Arts - Theater

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: The Rhode Island K-12 Grade Span Expectations in the Arts, has been developed as a means to identify the arts concepts and skills expected of all students. The RI arts GSEs encompass the content eligible for inclusion in local assessment in the arts in grades K - 12. They are not intended to represent the full arts curriculum at each grade span, but are meant to capture the "major ideas" of the art forms that can be assessed. The goal is that the arts GSEs focus the curriculum, but do not restrict it
Artistic Processes – Theater employs creative problem solving using tools, techniques, and technology in one or more disciplines in order to make the imagined tangible.
Students show skill development in acting, directing, designing, and scriptwriting by…

engaging in fantasy play; re-creating situations in familiar settings; beginning to dramatize or improvise familiar simple stories from classroom literature or life experiences; incorporating plot (beginning, middle, and end); and using a tableau, pantomime, or improvisation
performing imitative movements, rhythmical activities, and theater games (freeze, statues, and mirrors)
imitating and creating voices and feelings of people, animals and objects in various drama/theater experiences (e.g., skits, puppetry, pantomime, improvisation, fantasy play, storytelling)
using and creating simple costumes, props, music, or sets in dramatic activities
Students solve artistic problems by…
responding to suggested prompts and solutions
Students make connections among the arts and other disciplines by…

exploring the use of body, voice, and imagination to demonstrate an understanding of basic mathematical and social relationships (e.g., use movement and voice to demonstrate knowledge of concepts in addition and subtraction, or create a tableau that communicates friendship or hunger)
identifying the unique ways that theater tells a story compared to music, visual arts, and dance
Students show skill development in acting, directing, designing, and scriptwriting by…

retelling familiar stories; sequencing story points (what and when), identifying character (who), setting (where), and conflict (why); and beginning to participate in cooperative scriptwriting or improvisations that incorporate the five W's
identifying and performing knowledge of basic blocking and stage areas
demonstrating basic emotional traits of a character, based on literature, through gesture, action, and voice
designing or creating simple costumes, props, music, sets, makeup, or masks, based on literature, in basic formal or informal performances
Students solve artistic problems by…
exploring different strategies/techniques to create stories and environments
Students make connections among the arts and other disciplines by…

using body, voice, and imagination to describe concepts in nature and society with emphasis on the five W's (e.g., use movement and voice to demonstrate bird migration, or create an improvisation of the founding fathers signing the Declaration of Independence)
comparing the common devices for telling a story through theater and in writing (e.g., character, problem; beginning, middle, and end)
Students show skill development in acting, directing, designing, and scriptwriting by…

performing and exploring improvisational activities and describing complex ideas and universal themes in life and literature; and distinguishing between understanding of text, subtext, and context; writing and perform basic scenes or one-act plays that include a range of character types, monologue, dialogue, action, and setting
determining the use of blocking and stage areas, levels, and actor's position, such as full front, quarter, profile, and full back in dramatizations

using effective vocal expression, gesture, facial expression, timing, and language to create character in a comedic and dramatic situation; using sensory and emotional recall, and memorization skills to create a character
designing or creating costumes, props, music, sets, makeup, or masks that support or enhance character in basic formal or informal performances
Students solve artistic problems by…
generating strategies, and choosing one that addresses identified challenge inherent in the story (e.g., "How do we create a boat for Treasure Island using our bodies?")
Students make connections among the arts and other disciplines by…
using body, voice, and imagination to demonstrate the analysis of concepts in nature or society (e.g., collaborate in small group to study, design, and perform a concept, such as Manifest Destiny)
describing how the development of a character, writing a script, or designing a set integrates other art forms
Students show skill development in acting, directing, designing, and scriptwriting by…
creating basic characters, environments, and actions that exhibit tension and suspense; creating short dramatizations in selected styles of theater (e.g., melodrama, vaudeville, and musical theater)
analyzing and maintaining a rehearsal script/notebook to record directions and blocking, and design information

developing a character using non-verbal techniques (e.g., dance, mime, physical comedy, stage combat (wrestling, sword play, physical confrontation); using basic improvisation in rehearsal to discover character and motivation; developing a character as part of an ensemble
designing or creating, and analyzing costumes, props, music, sets, makeup, or masks that support or enhance character in formal or informal performances
Students solve artistic problems by…
researching and generating strategies, and choosing one that addresses identified challenge inherent in the story (e.g., "How do we foreshadow the antagonist's downfall?")
Students make connections among the arts and other disciplines by…

demonstrating analysis of a piece of literature or a social or scientific event by creating a short original dramatization (e.g., a musical scene from S.E. Hinton's Outsider or a video on cellular mitosis)
comparing and contrasting different theatrical performances to tell a similar story (e.g., plays and poetry both built on a journey theme)
Students show skill development in acting, directing, designing, and scriptwriting by…
writing dialogues and scenes, applying basic dramatic structure: exposition, complication, conflict, crises, climax, and resolution
developing stage directions for a play or performance based on a script

developing a character as part of an ensemble using vocal characteristics and techniques, posture, movement, and language necessary to perform an effective characterization; showing text analysis and research to include the physical, social, and psychological dimensions of the characters
designing or creating and analyzing designs that support or enhance the author's intent, based on text analysis and research
Students solve artistic problems by…
researching and generating strategies, and choosing one that addresses identified challenge inherent in the story (e.g., developing a metaphor of the protagonist's weakness)
Students make connections among the arts and other disciplines by…
demonstrating synthesis of a social or scientific conflict by performing a brief original dramatization (e.g., creationism vs. evolution)
analyzing and evaluating a theatrical performance for its effective use of music, dance, or visual arts
Students show skill development in acting, directing, designing, and scriptwriting by…

presenting an improvisation or scripted scene, applying basic dramatic structure (exposition, complication, conflict, crises, climax, and resolution) and including complex characters with unique dialogue that motivates the action
developing and evaluating the effectiveness of stage directions for a play or performance based on a script (e.g., notebook that records reflection and revision throughout the rehearsal process
creating and presenting a character as part of an ensemble from classical, contemporary, realistic, or nonrealistic dramatic texts
designing and creating designs for a play that enhance the author's intent, based on culture, history, and stage design
Students solve artistic problems by…
researching, generating, and implementing strategies that enhance the story (e.g., analyzing character's strengths and vulnerabilities and exploiting them in a disciplined and insightful performance)
Students make connections among the arts and other disciplines by…

demonstrating research and synthesis of concepts from literature, the social sciences, or scientific conflict by performing an original dramatization (e.g., Eleanor Roosevelt's platform speech as a candidate for president in the current time)

researching and evaluating how a particular set designer's visual elements express time, place, and mood (how effectively the set pieces show us we are in a Restoration comedy based on color, shape, line, and placement of set pieces)
Cultural Contexts – Theater arts creatively expresses the values and ideas of human experience, community, and civilization.
Students demonstrate knowledge and understanding of the role of Theater Arts in personal, cultural, and historical context by…
retelling or dramatizing a story, myth, fable, or fairy tale from two cultures and times
recognizing how the theater arts are different and similar in different cultures and times
describing ways in which theater, television, electronic media, and film influence their thinking in positive and negative ways
role-playing adult professions using creative dramatics and theatrical activities
Students demonstrate knowledge and understanding of the role of Theater Arts in personal, cultural, and historical context by…
retelling and dramatizing a story, character, and design element drawn from at least two historical/cultural periods
describing in broad terms how the theater arts are different and similar in different cultures and times
identifying ways in which theater, television, electronic media, and film influence their thinking in positive and negative ways
describing the roles of the arts and artist in society to communicate stories, events, and feelings
Students demonstrate knowledge and understanding of the role of Theater Arts in personal, cultural, and historical context by…
describing and dramatizing two stories with a common theme from two historical periods or cultures (e.g., freedom, triumph over adversity)
identifying specific cultural beliefs and traditions in the theater arts in at least two cultures and time periods
analyzing ways in which theater, television, electronic media, and film influence their thinking in positive and negative ways
selecting or creating appropriate props, sets, and costumes for a cultural celebration or pageant
describing the roles of the arts and artists in society to interpret events and cultures, to innovate and take risks while solving problems
describing a career opportunity and identifying the education required to be an artist
Students demonstrate knowledge and understanding of the role of Theater Arts in personal, cultural, and historical context by…
analyzing and dramatizing two stories with a common theme from two historical periods or cultures (e.g., loyalty, revenge, redemption)

comparing and contrasting cultural beliefs and traditions in the theater arts in two cultures and time periods (e.g., Greek theater - comedy and tragedy; Japanese Theater – Kabuki, Noh; American theater - melodrama and musical theater)
interpreting and evaluating ways in which theater, television, electronic media, or film influence their thinking in positive and negative ways
designing and creating masks, puppets, props, costumes, music, or sets in a selected theatrical style drawn from world cultures, such as Japanese shadow puppets or Kabuki masks
analyzing the roles of the arts and artists in times of conflict and harmony to express disapproval and unity
describing at least two different artistic careers and the education required
Students demonstrate knowledge and understanding of the role of Theater Arts in personal, cultural, and historical context by…
evaluating and applying historic or cultural techniques to an original story

interpreting and evaluating cultural beliefs and traditions in the theater arts in two cultures and time periods (e.g., Ancient Greece, Commedia dell'arte, Medieval, Classical and Contemporary, Kabuki theater, African-American, Hispanic, Middle Eastern)
researching and evaluating ways that theater, television, electronic media, and film influence their lives in positive and negative ways
Researching cultural and historical references to design and create production elements
analyzing different culture's expectations and appreciation of the role of the artists in society
analyzing two different career opportunities and learning pathways to be a professional artist
Students demonstrate knowledge and understanding of the role of Theater Arts in personal, cultural, and historical context by…
researching a cultural, philosophical, ethical, or religious issue described in the theater arts and presenting an influenced original work
presenting researched interpretation and evaluation of a particular playwright's work from a particular period of time or culture and defend the evidence that holds the works together
researching censorship policies and defend conclusion regarding the influence of theater, television, and film
Performing, designing, or directing theater pieces in specific theatrical styles (e.g., by such playwrights as Sophocles, Shakespeare, Lope de Vega, Aphra Behn, Moliere, and Chekhov)
researching a culture's expectation and appreciation of the role of the artist in society
analyzing and evaluating a specific career opportunity and determining which learning pathway will lead to that career
Communication – Theater communicates meaning and expression through the sharing of human experience using image, sound, movement, words, space, time and chronology.
Students demonstrate the ability to communicate in the language of the Theater Arts by…
exploring techniques to convey ideas, feelings, or meaning (e.g., act out as the weather, create a soundscape of a storm)
Students demonstrate the ability to extract meaning from Theater by…
identifying important character traits and big ideas and emotions told in the story
Students demonstrate the ability to communicate in the language of the Theater Arts by…
identifying and applying performance and design techniques to convey ideas, feelings, or meaning (e.g., body language and voice that expresses emotions of pride, fear)
Students demonstrate the ability to extract meaning from Theater by…
describing and interpreting character traits and connecting them to the ideas and emotions told in the story
Students demonstrate the ability to communicate in the language of the Theater Arts by…
selecting and applying performance and design techniques to convey a range of ideas, feelings, or meaning (e.g., a little sad to very sad; disappointed to crushed)
Students demonstrate the ability to extract meaning from Theater by…
analyzing major themes and characters and their symbolic representations (i.e., cultural references)
identifying important techniques that support the story's meaning (e.g., set design)
Students demonstrate the ability to communicate in the language of the Theater Arts by…
analyzing and applying performance and design techniques to convey complex emotions, ideas, or meaning (e.g., betrayal or enlightenment or in aspects of design or writing)
Students demonstrate the ability to extract meaning from Theater by…
analyzing major and minor themes and characters and their symbolic representation (i.e., cultural references)
analyzing techniques that support the story's meaning (e.g., the lighting in combination with the music foreshadowed hope)
Students demonstrate the ability to communicate in the language of the Theater Arts by…

evaluating and applying performance and design techniques to convey evolving ideas, feelings, or meaning (e.g., connecting particular gestures with phrasing to imply a sense of place and social stature and how this behavior evolves as the character's life unravels or in aspects of design or writing)
Students demonstrate the ability to extract meaning from Theater by…
evaluating major and minor themes and characters and their symbolic representation (i.e., cultural references)
evaluating techniques for their effectiveness and craft (e.g., critiquing actor's performance and the playwright's dialog)
Students demonstrate the ability to communicate in the language of the Theater Arts by…

evaluating and applying performance and design techniques to convey contrasting ideas, feelings, or meaning (e.g., utilizing developed skills to effectively perform tragic or comic roles or in aspects of design or writing)
Students demonstrate the ability to extract meaning from Theater by…
researching and evaluating major and minor themes and characters and their symbolic representation (i.e., cultural references) from the works of a particular playwright, culture, or period
researching and evaluating a particular playwright's choice of techniques for their effectiveness and craft in two or more of her/his works
Aesthetic Judgment – Applying knowledge and skills of Theater Arts in order to reflect on and evaluate the work of self and others.
Students reflect upon, analyze and evaluate the work of self and others by…
identifying what is seen and heard in a performance using theater vocabulary (real or imaginary people, basic character traits, etc.)
Students reflect upon, analyze and evaluate the work of self and others by…

describing what is seen (e.g., setting, props, costumes, scenery) and heard (e.g., voice projection, diction, pace, and volume) in a performance and comparing that with things known (e.g., time, place, cultural identification, etc.)
interpreting character's objectives and motivations based on what is seen, heard, and known to explain character's behavior
Students reflect upon, analyze and evaluate the work of self and others by…

describing what is seen (e.g., setting, props, costumes, scenery) and heard (e.g., voice projection, diction, pace, and volume) in a performance or text and comparing that with things known (e.g., time period, place, cultural identification, etc.)
interpreting character's objectives and motivations based on what is seen, heard, and known to explain character's behavior

identifying technical elements of a theatrical production (e.g., sense memory, script, act, scene, beat, cue, monologue, dialogue, action/reaction, subtext, theme, mood, gesture, rehearsal, design, performance, director, production values, and stage crew)
identifying the dramatic elements of plot (e.g., exposition, complication, crisis, climax, and resolution) in a script or performance
Students reflect upon, analyze and evaluate the work of self and others by…

analyzing what is seen and heard (e.g., figurative language and imagery) in a performance or text and comparing that with things known (e.g., the playwright, time period, place, cultural identification, etc.)
evaluating character's objectives and motivations based on what is seen, heard, and known to explain character's behavior
analyzing technical elements of a theatrical production (e.g., playwright, dress rehearsal, run-through, cold reading, ensemble, proscenium, thrust, and arena staging)
analyzing dramatic elements of a plot (e.g., recurring themes and patterns, protagonist and antagonist, foreshadowing, rising action, catharsis, and denouncement)
Students reflect upon, analyze and evaluate the work of self and others by…
evaluating a play or performances based on analysis of what is seen, heard, and known to judge its value and contribution to humanity
evaluating character's objectives and motivations based on what is seen, heard, and known to explain character's behavior
evaluating technical elements of theatrical production
evaluating dramatic elements of a plot for their effectiveness and cohesiveness
Students reflect upon, analyze and evaluate the work of self and others by…

researching and evaluating two or more plays or performances that share a common theme, playwright or other aspect, based on analysis of what is seen, heard, and known, to judge its value to humanity and contribution to the theater arts
researching two or more classic character types and analyzing how they have been characterized in theater and comparing the type to famous or infamous actual people, presenting a conclusion
evaluating the production elements of a school or community play or performance and defend the value (e.g., contracts and unions, costs, lighting, ticket sales, logistical plan)
directing a play or performance
